OUTLINE TERMS OF REFERENCE FOR CONSULTANTS 
1.  Nine national consultants (team leader, deputy team leader, and seven other thematic 
experts) and one international consultant will be engaged for this technical assistance (TA). The 
consultants will be engaged by the Asian Development Bank (ADB) following its Guidelines on 
the Use of Consultants (2010, as amended from time to time). 

2.  Environmental  legislation  specialist  (ecosystems  and  natural  resources) 
(international,  3.5  person-months).  An  international  environmental  legislation  specialist  with 
knowledge of payment for ecological services (PES) and eco-compensation will support the 
national team leader and deputy team leader. The consultant will have the following specific 
responsibilities: 
(i)  work  with  the  team  leader  to  refine  the  overall  study  framework;  scope  of 
thematic studies; and outlines of the inception, interim, and final TA reports; 
(ii)  provide guidance to the team leader on international best practice technical input 
relating to the PES-related environmental legislation; 
(iii)  identify appropriate agencies and organizations in the target countries for the 
foreign legislation review mission, and liaise with agencies and organizations 
regarding the mission program; 
(iv)  assist the team leader in preparing participants for foreign legislation review 
missions, and outline specific tasks and responsibilities for mission members 
based on their specific expertise; 
(v)  review and provide comments on reports prepared by the legislation drafting 
team;  
(vi)  support the team leader in consolidating the inputs from the specialists carrying 
out the nine thematic studies; 
(vii)  contribute to drafting and review of the inception, interim, and final TA reports; 
(viii)  participate  in  project  workshops  (inception,  midterm,  and  final)  and  other 
seminars presenting the TA results;  
(ix)  in  consultation  with  ADB,  prepare  an  appropriate  knowledge  product  to 
synthesize the key lessons and outputs of the TA; and 
(x)  provide input to other related technical tasks as requested by the team leader. 

3.  Team leader and environmental legislation specialist (national, 9 person-months). 
The  environmental  legislation  specialist  will  be  responsible  for  overall  coordination  and 
supervision  of  the  TA  activities  and  outputs  and  day-to-day  liaison  with  the  National 
Development  and  Reform  Commission  (NDRC)  and  other  national  government  agencies 
supporting the related work. The environment legislation specialist will  
(i)  develop the overall detailed study framework; and drafting of the TA inception, 
midterm, and final reports, along with the international environmental legislation 
specialist;   
(ii)  review and coordinate individual studies, and organize workshops; 
(iii)  function as leading expert on the thematic study area legislative framework for 
eco-compensation; 
(iv)  develop and refine the specific terms of reference for the thematic experts of the 
remaining seven thematic study areas; 
(v)  manage and ensure timely implementation of the project activities; 
(vi)  review and assess international experiences (including coordination of the study 
tour) in drafting and implementing PES-related legislation, and prepare a report; 
(vii)  prepare  the  national  eco-compensation  drafting  team  for  the  respective 
international legislation review mission, and coordinate the legislation review;

12  Appendix 4 

PROPOSED OUTLINE OF THE THEMATIC STUDY REPORTS  
(e.g., for the wetland thematic area) 

1.  The literature review on payment for ecosystem services for wetlands around the world 
and eco-compensation for wetlands in the People’s Republic of China will include 
(i)  cases of payment for ecosystem services of wetlands around the world; 
(ii)  lessons from international experience; 
(iii)  cases of eco-compensation for wetlands in the People’s Republic of China;  
(iv)  relevant  national  or  local  laws,  regulations,  and  policies  on  wetland  eco-
compensation; and  
(v)  lessons from existing eco-compensation for wetlands in the PRC.  

2.  Field studies will include 
(i)  institutional  framework  in  the  case  site  where  a  wetland  eco-compensation 
program is being designed, prepared, and discussed; 
(ii)  social,  economic,  and  environmental  characteristics  of  the  case  site:  status, 
problems, vision; 
(iii)  stakeholder analysis; 
(iv)  economic analysis; 
(v)  financial management and analysis; and  
(vi)  monitoring and evaluation. 

3.  Lessons for legislation of eco-compensation legislation include 
(i)  lessons from past experience and from field case study; and  
(ii)  recommendations for legislation.
